\begin_layout Title
The Polylog and the Riemann Hypothesis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Linas Vepstas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
29 October 2023
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
The Riemann Hypothesis can be restated as a hypothesis about the zeros of
 the polylog function.
 The relationship is quite simple, clear and direct: the nontrivial zeros
 of the Riemann zeta are in direct correspondence with the zeros of the
 polylog.
 This correspondence allows RH to be refined into two distinct vrsions:
 a strong form, where polylog zeros are uniformly bounded away, and a weak
 form, where RH holds, but flirts with failure.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
The correspondence between polylog zeros and RH zeros can be clearly seen
 in animations of the polylog function along the critical strip, posted
 posted on the linas.org website (See 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "https://linas.org/art-gallery/polylog/polylog.html"
target "https://linas.org/art-gallery/polylog/polylog.html"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) This short note is meant to accompany and explain those animations, providing
 additional detail and explanations not given on the website.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
The animations provide insight that is otherwise difficult to obtain: the
 polylog function has a complicated behavior, due in part to it's having
 two branch points, and participates in many identities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The polylog function has the series expansion 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{Li}_{s}\left(z\right)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{z^{n}}{n^{s}}
\]

\end_inset

This converges for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|z\right|<1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Re s>1$
\end_inset

.
 Analytic continuation can be used to extend this to other values of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 Comparing the above to the series representation for the Riemann zeta
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\zeta\left(s\right)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n^{s}}
\]

\end_inset

one is tempted to make a naive (but entirely incorrect) algebraic manipulation
 that suggests 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta\left(s\right)=\mbox{Li}_{s}\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 But this is false.
 The problem is that the polylogarithm has a branch point (essential singularity
) at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset

; the polylog has many sheets, wrapped as a helix around 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset

.
 The naive identity cannot hold.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although one does not have this simple relationship between the Riemann
 zeta and the polylogarithm, one still has a behavior that makes it 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

almost true
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Zeros of the polylogarithm 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hit
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the branch point exactly when 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a nontrivial Riemann zero.
 The relation is deeper: it seems that the zeros of the polylogarithm, when
 viewed on the critical line 
\begin_inset Formula $s=1/2+i\tau$
\end_inset

, are in exact correspondence with the nontrivial zeros of the Riemann zeta.
\end_layout

